{
  "query": "How do the outcomes of translocating marine mammals vary depending on the conservation goal, based on studies from the Pacific and Tasman Sea regions?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies from the Pacific and Tasman Sea regions, marine mammal translocation outcomes vary significantly depending on conservation goals. For population re-establishment goals in the North Pacific Ocean, four studies on Hawaiian monk seals showed positive outcomes: 50-83% of translocated seal pups survived for at least one year, with translocated pups having similar survival rates to non-translocated pups born at release sites or greater survival rates than non-translocated pups remaining at the original site. More than a quarter of translocated Hawaiian monk seals reproduced, and more than a quarter survived when translocation was combined with at least seven other survival enhancement interventions. Translocated Hawaiian monk seal pups also showed similar dispersal times to non-translocated seal pups born at release sites (Action ID: 2930). In contrast, for human-wildlife conflict reduction goals in the Tasman Sea and Southern Ocean around Tasmania, two studies found that translocation was less effective: more than half or nearly all of Australian and New Zealand fur seals translocated away from salmon farms returned to the original location (Action ID: 2776).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2930",
    "2776"
  ]
}

