{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the long-term survival of marine mammals following rescue or rehabilitation and release?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence for long-term survival of marine mammals following rescue or rehabilitation and release comes from multiple studies. For rehabilitated and released injured, sick or weak marine mammals, 21 studies found that 10-100% of dolphins, porpoises, whales, seals, sea lions and manatees survived during post-release monitoring periods ranging from three days to five years (Action 2925). For rescued and released stranded or trapped marine mammals, seven studies found that 17-100% of Atlantic white-sided dolphins, short-beaked common dolphins, common bottlenose dolphins, long-finned pilot whales, short-finned pilot whales, and Cape fur seals survived during post-release monitoring periods ranging from three weeks to three years (Action 2924). \n\nSpecific long-term survival evidence includes: more than a quarter of rehabilitated and released Hawaiian monk seals reproduced (Action 2925), a stranded common bottlenose dolphin was observed with a calf a year later after rescue and release (Action 2924), and more than a quarter of Hawaiian monk seals survived after rescue, release and other interventions (Action 2924). For hand-reared orphaned mammals, approximately three-quarters of Antillean manatees and two-thirds of Florida manatees that were captive-reared and released were known to survive for at least one year, with some surviving for more than seven years (Action 2926). Captive-reared and released Pacific harbour seal pups had similar survival estimates to wild pups (Action 2926). For captive-bred releases, two of three Antillean manatees and two of 14 Florida manatees born in captivity survived for at least one year without further intervention (Action 2933).",
